1. **YouTube Channels:**
	* **Mig Jimenez** (Mig Productions): A master of weathering and aging effects.","evidence_reason":"The transcript contains a reusable set of weathering methods and named resources recommended for the user's current model builds.","importance":4,"keywords":["weathering","aging effects","washes","drybrushing","chipping","powder pigments","Mig Jimenez","The Weathering Magazine","Scalemates","Model Mayhem","Scalemodeling.net","The Weathering Aircraft","Ferrari 288 GTO","Japanese Zero"],"note_type":"context","rationale":"This is not a single atomic fact; it preserves a compact recommendation set and technique context that can be reused when advising on the user's model weathering work.","scope_json":{"basis":"summarized","kind":"conversation","text":"Weathering and aging-effect resources discussed for the user's Ferrari 288 GTO and Japanese Zero model builds in the 2023-05-24 session"},"summary":"For the user's Ferrari 288 GTO and 1/48 scale Japanese Zero model, reusable weathering guidance included studying real references, using a solid base coat, applying subtle layered effects, and combining washes, drybrushing, chipping, rust/corrosion, and powder pigments. Recommended resources named Mig Jimenez, The Weathering Magazine, Scalemates, Model Mayhem, Scalemodeling.net, and The Weathering Aircraft by Mig Jimenez.","tags":["scale_modeling","weathering","resources"],"title":"Weathering and resource guidance for Ferrari 288 GTO and Japanese Zero models","valid_from":"2023-05-24T21:33:00+03:00","valid_to":null},{"candidate_claim_hints":["The user recently got a new airbrush compressor and some acrylic paints."],"confidence":0.93,"entity_refs":[{"entity_id":"entity:<0>","role":"owner"},{"entity_id":"entity:<3>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<4>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<12>","role":"mentioned"},{"entity_id":"entity:<13>","role":"mentioned"},{"entity_id":"entity:<14>","role":"mentioned"}],"evidence_kind":"summarized","evidence_quote":"Start with a 1:1 ratio (paint:thinner) and adjust as needed.","evidence_reason":"The transcript provides a procedural set of practical settings and workflow tips for achieving smooth coats with the user's new airbrush setup.","importance":4,"keywords":["airbrush","airbrush compressor","acrylic paints","1:1 ratio","10-15 PSI","Vallejo Airbrush Thinner","Tamiya Acrylic Thinner","Vallejo Model Air","primer","clear coat"],"note_type":"lesson","rationale":"The value is a reusable procedure and parameter set rather than a clean atomic claim.","scope_json":{"basis":"summarized","kind":"entity","text":"Practical airbrushing workflow for the user's new airbrush compressor and acrylic paints"},"summary":"The user's airbrush approach should emphasize practice, correct nozzle size, thinning acrylics starting around 1:1 paint:thinner, testing roughly 10–15 PSI, holding the airbrush about 1–2 inches from the model at a 90-degree angle, using gentle strokes and thin layers, cleaning regularly, and considering Vallejo Airbrush Thinner, Tamiya Acrylic Thinner, primer, sanding, Vallejo Model Air, and clear coat for smoother finishes.","tags":["scale_modeling","airbrushing","painting"],"title":"Airbrush practice approach for smooth acrylic coats","valid_from":"2023-05-24T21:33:00+03:00","valid_to":null},{"candidate_claim_hints":[],"confidence":0.92,"entity_refs":[{"entity_id":"entity:<2>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<15>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<16>","role":"mentioned"},{"entity_id":"entity:<0>","role":"owner"}],"evidence_kind":"summarized","evidence_quote":"The Zero's Nakajima Sakae engine was notorious for leaking oil and producing a lot of grime.","evidence_reason":"The transcript gives named, model-specific weathering patterns and techniques for the Mitsubishi A6M Zero and the user's Japanese Zero build.","importance":5,"keywords":["Japanese Zero","Mitsubishi A6M Zero","Nakajima Sakae engine","WWII Japanese aircraft","oxidation","chalking","oil stains","engine grime","fabric wear","weathering"],"note_type":"context","rationale":"This captures reusable domain guidance and trade-offs for a specific model, not merely a single factual assertion.","scope_json":{"basis":"summarized","kind":"entity","text":"Weathering guidance for the user's 1/48 scale Japanese Zero fighter plane model representing a Mitsubishi A6M Zero"},"summary":"For the user's Japanese Zero model, the relevant WWII Japanese aircraft weathering pattern is subtle but layered: oxidation/corrosion from saltwater and humidity, fading and chalking from tropical sun, grime and oil stains from leaky engines, dust from rough airfields, rust around rivets and joints, Nakajima Sakae engine grime around cowling and exhausts, and fabric wear on control surfaces. The recommended modeling approach is a faded base coat plus restrained washes, drybrushing, and powders rather than heavy over-weathering.","tags":["scale_modeling","aircraft_weathering","japanese_zero"],"title":"Mitsubishi A6M Zero WWII weathering pattern guidance","valid_from":"2023-05-24T21:33:00+03:00","valid_to":null},{"candidate_claim_hints":["The user plans to start by adding a pilot figure and maybe ground equipment like fuel drums or ammo crates to the Japanese Zero fighter plane model.","The user plans to consider texture and weathering effects for a Japanese Zero airfield diorama.","The user likes the idea of adding a racing mechanic figure and miniature toolbox to the Ferrari 288 GTO model."],"confidence":0.96,"entity_refs":[{"entity_id":"entity:<0>","role":"owner"},{"entity_id":"entity:<2>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<1>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<17>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<18>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<19>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<20>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<21>","role":"secondary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<22>","role":"mentioned"},{"entity_id":"entity:<23>","role":"mentioned"},{"entity_id":"entity:<24>","role":"mentioned"}],"evidence_kind":"direct","evidence_quote":"I'll definitely keep in mind the importance of balance and subtlety when adding details, and focus on creating a compelling story with my diorama.","evidence_reason":"The user explicitly states the planned accessories and the design principle for adding details to both model dioramas.","importance":5,"keywords":["diorama","storytelling","pilot figure","fuel drums","ammo crates","airfield diorama","racing mechanic","miniature toolbox","racing helmet","pit board","trackside scene","grandstands"],"note_type":"plan","rationale":"This is a multi-part design direction with rationale and constraints, better represented as a plan note than isolated claims.","scope_json":{"basis":"explicit","kind":"conversation","text":"Diorama detail direction for the user's Japanese Zero and Ferrari 288 GTO models in the 2023-05-24 session"},"summary":"The user is exploring diorama storytelling details for both builds: for the Japanese Zero, a pilot figure, fuel drums or ammo crates, and a battle-worn textured airfield diorama; for the Ferrari 288 GTO, a racing mechanic figure, miniature toolbox, and possible racing helmet, pit board, or trackside scene with grandstands and other racing cars. The guiding constraint is to keep details balanced and subtle while creating a compelling scene.","tags":["scale_modeling","diorama","storytelling"],"title":"Diorama storytelling plan for Japanese Zero and Ferrari 288 GTO models","valid_from":"2023-05-24T21:33:00+03:00","valid_to":null},{"candidate_claim_hints":["The user is considering adding opening doors or movable parts to their models."],"confidence":0.91,"entity_refs":[{"entity_id":"entity:<0>","role":"owner"},{"entity_id":"entity:<2>","role":"primary"},{"entity_id":"entity:<1>","role":"primary"}],"evidence_kind":"summarized","evidence_quote":"Adding opening doors or movable parts can take your models to the next level of realism and interactivity.","evidence_reason":"The transcript provides a structured recommendation list for implementing functional details in the user's models.","importance":4,"keywords":["opening doors","movable parts","hinges","pins","ailerons","elevators","rudder","flaps","airbrakes","cockpit canopy","engine hatch","Ferrari 288 GTO","Japanese Zero"],"note_type":"lesson","rationale":"This is reusable procedure/design guidance, not a precise factual claim.","scope_json":{"basis":"summarized","kind":"conversation","text":"Practical guidance for adding opening doors and movable parts to the user's scale model builds"},"summary":"For adding opening doors or movable parts, the reusable guidance is to plan mechanisms early, use suitable thin metal/plastic plus hinges and pins, keep mechanisms simple, model real movement from reference images, test and refine for smooth operation, add hinge/latch/handle details last, and check balance, durability, display, and storage impacts. Examples include ailerons, elevators, rudder, flaps, or airbrakes on the Japanese Zero and cockpit canopies, engine hatches, or doors on the Ferrari 288 GTO.","tags":["scale_modeling","movable_parts","model_engineering"],"title":"Guidelines for opening doors and movable parts in scale models","valid_from":"2023-05-24T21:33:00+03:00","valid_to":null}]}
